reason.tex:
%text Logarithms can be taken on any base $b\gt 0$.
That said, \underline\text{if $b\neq e$}, then % \begin{align} \log_b x^y &= \log_b e^{x-y} \\ \implies y\cdot\log_b x &= (x-y)\cdot\underbrace{ \log_b e}_{\neq 1} \end{align} \\ %text
However, \underline\text{if $b=e$}, then % \begin{align} \log_e x^y &= \log_e e^{x-y} \\ \implies y\cdot\log_e x &= (x-y)\cdot\underbrace{ \log_e e}_{= 1} \\ \implies y\cdot \log x &= (x-y) \end{align}

\begin{align}
y\cdot\log x = (x-y) &\implies y\cdot (\log x + 1) = x \\
\therefore y &= \frac{x}{\log x + 1} \\
\text{Hence, }\frac{dy}{dx} &= 
\underbrace{\frac{(\log x + 1) - x\cdot\frac{1}{x}}{(\log x + 1)^2}}_{\text{Quotient Rule}} \\
&= \frac{\log x }{(\log x + 1)^2}
\end{align}

options.tex:
\begin{align}
\log x + 1 &= \log x + \log e = \log (x\cdot e) \\
\therefore \frac{dy}{dx} &= \frac{\log x}{\lbrace \log (x\cdot e)\rbrace^2}
\end{align}

reason.tex:
%text
We know that \[ \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{\log x}{(\log x + 1)^2} \]

But given that we have been taking 
logarithms \underline\text{to the base $e$}, it also 
follows that 

%
\begin{align}
\log x + 1 &= \log x + \underbrace{\log e}_{=1} 
= \underbrace{\log (x\cdot e)}_{\log a + \log b = \log (a\cdot b)} \\
\therefore \frac{dy}{dx} &= \frac{\log x}{(\log x + 1)^2} = 
\frac{\log x}{\lbrace \log (x\cdot e)\rbrace^2}
\end{align}
